Lethal Force to prove decisive in July Cup at Newmarket
Clive Cox’s expertise in developing raw racing talent comes under the microscope again as in-form Lethal Force seeks to step up on his Royal Ascot triumph by winning Saturday's Darley July Cup at Newmarket.
On the up: Lethal Force is progressing fast and can add the July Cup to his Royal Ascot success Photo: GETTY IMAGES	By J A McGrath
6:49PM BST 12 Jul 2013
Comments
The four-year-old lived up to encouraging reports of his progress with an emphatic victory in the Diamond Jubilee Stakes, over six furlongs. He finished off his race really strongly, suggesting he is well up to another major success against similar opposition.
Cox is gaining a reputation for moulding and developing young horses and Lethal Force is an excellent example of his skill. There is no reason why this sprinter should not go on improving and I fancy him to get the better of South African challenger Shea Shea and the King’s Stand winner Sole Power.
Shea Shea was caught close to home by Sole Power in the King’s Stand over five furlongs at the Royal meeting, but there is enough evidence to suggest the latter is better over five furlongs than six and I expect this to prove a completely different test.
Another feasible option is the Aidan O’Brien-trained Gale Force Ten, who won the Jersey Stakes at Royal Ascot. In an interesting move O’Brien will fit blinkers for the first time to the three-year-old. With the added advantage of Ryan Moore in the saddle, he could prove the biggest danger.
Not only is there high-class racing at Newmarket, York, Ascot and Chester, the French supply one of the highlights of the weekend in the Group One Juddmonte Grand Prix de Paris at Longchamp. Once again, the Epsom Derby form faces a thorough examination.
