Parents using GPS tags to monitor their child's whereabouts
Growing numbers of parents are turning to technology to allay their anxieties about their children’s whereabouts by getting them to wear satellite tracking devices.
'Freedom for Kids' devices are designed to simply clip onto a child’s wrist By Rebecca McGann, and John Bingham
7:30AM BST 30 Jun 2013
Comments
Barely distinguishable from a wrist watch, the systems use a combination of the technology in motorists’ sat nav devices and methods used by police to track criminals by their mobile phone signal.
Already popular in the US, internet retailers have reported a steady growth in sales in Britain as parents try to reconcile calls from experts to give their children greater freedom to play, with anxiety about traffic and strangers.
In a vivid illustration of how technology is transforming family life, some parents are using them to keep tabs on older children as they travel the world on gap years. Meanwhile children have also begun to use them as a “bargaining tool” with their parents, agreeing to wear one in return for permission to go out with their friends. Charities said they could prove a pragmatic extra protection for older children but cautioned that parents could be lulled into a “false sense of security”.
GPS tracking devices and tags are already widely used for wandering pets as well as, controversially, dementia patients living at home.
