One retailer which markets cords fitted with tracking devices for elderly people claims to have sold its products to social care departments in 90 per cent of local authorities.
Variants for children have, until recently, remained a niche market, largely confined to special schools and parts of the criminal justice system.
The devices work by sending a satellite signal to a computer or mobile phone. The parent then logs onto their account via the internet or can send a text to a special number to receive a message back indicating the wearer’s location, accurate to within 10ft. Steve Salmon, chief executive of the specialist GPS supplier “Lok8u”, said that while the bulk of orders for his “Freedom for Kids” devices are from the US, he now sells up to 200 devices a month in the UK. The devices are marketed for children as young as five and designed to simply clip onto a child’s wrist. Prices start from £100. Mr Salmon said he had noticed an annual pattern with sales peaking in July as the school holidays begin, and again in late August as parents prepare to send their children back to school. He added that he had more inquiries in the wake of the disappearance of five-year-old April Jones in North Wales last year.
Mark Carfe, chief executive of Trackershop-uk, another supplier, said he sells about 150 trackers a month to British parents, with sales rising by 20 per cent in the last year.
“It is not the case that parents want to snoop on where or what their children are doing so much as that they want an added sense of security from knowing that their children are indeed where they should be,” he said.
“If something untoward should happen they can be alerted, 24 hours a day, globally and instantly. Our trackers do all of this.”
But he said there were also unexpected uses – with students even using them to produce digital souvenirs of their gap years. “The tracker is recording all of its movements, so is a fantastic way of replaying a holiday, school trip or gap year travel,” he said.
A spokesman for the NSPCC said that the devices could be helpful if used alongside more traditional ways of supervising their children but expressed reservations. “I’m not sure we would promote or endorse them as they could breed a false sense of security; there is no proof they will help,” he said.
“Just because you know where the GPS is doesn’t definitely mean you know it’s still with the child or even that you can get there quickly.”
